            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.63-64_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">6<del/><add>3</add></fw>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>May 4, 1958</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I have just heard the news about Mrs Neihardt's passing and though life inures you to its vicissitudes it still can never inculcate a feeling of complete acceptance. My love for Mrs Neihardt was far greater than the amount of times we saw each other would indicate. I was accepted as if I was family from the first time I walked into your house and every suceeding<sic>succeeding</sic> time Mrs Neihardt would say, John and I are so glad you visited and I know that was true. I brought friends, dates, and classmates to visit your house<del/> just as I would do if it was my own home.</p>
                
                <p>Your relation with Mrs. Neihardt was inspirational to me because you always reminded me of a couple that were just engaged and full of the feeling of a first romance. To keep that feeling through all your married life is remarkable. Besides there was always that mutual respect and admiration for each other that I so admired. I am getting married June 8th and I sincerely hope that my marriage will be an emulation of yours.</p>
                
                <p>Both of us are familiar with the power of words; yet we also know there are times that feelings cannot be transcribed into another media. Sometime when we are together I will be able to say what I cannot write. Onr<sic>One</sic> thin<del>h</del><add>g</add> I am sure of though. And that is that I know of no one else who I feel could accept such a gre<del>ta<unclear/></del><add>at l</add>oss with as complete an understanding as y<del>i</del><add>o</add>u. Your whole philosophy and pattern of life and the true greatn ss<sic>greatness</sic> of the relationship you have shared has prepared you. I am just thankful that I was privileged to see that relationship in action.</p>
                
                <p>If you are still going to lecture <del>in</del> at Cornell the 21st and will be in New York City at all please let me know. I have plenty of room at my home for you to stay and would enjoy seeing you again.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Fondly,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Bob Leaf</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
